segments.text: and then selected Jarvis Miller as president.
Were you still a commandant?
I was in the police department.
I went to the police department in the summer of 77.
Okay, before Dr. Miller became president.
All right, describe how that change came.
Well, it didn't really affect me.
Woodall took over my job.
But how were you selected as president?
John Coldis, he was having problems with the police department because the police chief over there was a good old guy, you know, passed away and took the ringer and the son of the other.
But he had a couple of women employees ask for jobs and he said, I got my quota of women and things like that.
And he needed somebody over there that was a little more attuned to life today.
And so he asked me about taking on that job and that position.
And I said I wouldn't be very interested in it, and so I just moved from one to the other.
I took military leave for my last 30 days and started working for the university.
And you reported directly to Coldis.
Right.
Did he give you any directions or guidance?
One thing they wanted to do was to try to improve the image of the police with the students and the staff faculty.
And there was no way really that it could happen with the parking situation the way it was.
And that was the best thing that ever happened as far as police was concerned was
separating it and having a traffic and a police.
That's really why I left.
I had all of it I could stomach.
I was taken it home with me and nothing I could do about it.
And we really were concerned, but you're personally blamed for it.
And, you know, that parking garage is there now.
We recommended that way, way back.
And we did a parking study that
about half of the one that they adopted, they included into that thing, and I'm sure that company used what we'd spent time trying to work out, about gates and all this other stuff.
Not near as sophisticated as this, but it was a miserable job.
When you took over as campus security and traffic, how many professionals were there in those units?
The total commissioned officers was 49 and we had 8 or 10 secretaries and we had 10 or 12 student workers.
Did you inherit any problems right off that you had to?

Oh yeah, I inherited the one on not hiring another woman and, you know, we have equal opportunities people and we got that straightened out and we offered her a job and she didn't want to come to the police department after that but they got her a job on campus making more money and we had, you know, we're always getting threatened, we're going to sue you, this, that, or the other and I paid for that parking spot and
All that stuff, so you spent most of the time doing that.
We had the wrong person dealing with complaints.
Maddox was not a very popular person, and I don't know that he was treating people fairly.
Probably wasn't.
And Bob White did the right thing getting rid of him.
And Russ McDonald, I did the wrong thing making him police chief.
I did it because he was the finest sergeant major I ever had, but he couldn't forget that he was sergeant major.
And he handled the police pretty much the same way, and that's the wrong way.
But he did some good things too.
And I might mention here something you probably don't know,
But the program that the police have where if you want to turn somebody in and get the money, what do you call it?
I forget the number.
We don't want your name.
We just want your information.
It started with Rush McDonald for the state of Texas.

He went to New Mexico to represent the police department in a police meeting and New Mexico had used that system and he came back with it and they were all excited about it and I said, well, go to work on it and see what you can do.
And we got together with the college station in Brown and set one up and we provided an officer full time to answer the phone
And he got the community to support the money and then he carried it before the Texas people and the police business and they got adopted.
So we were the people in the state of Texas for that program.
Now, when you took over, the headquarters was where the development foundation building is now.
Right.
And in terms of the hour demands on your time,
How did that job compare with Commandant?
Well, I pretty well went home at 5 o'clock, but my phone rang after that, and it was not a fun job, so I went home with my problems.
Were there any high moments, pleasant moments?
Well, most of the people were good people to work with and we'd go over there and visit them every time we'd come down here.
We were really pleased with them and a lot of them are still around here.
But I didn't, not very many people ever said thank you.
And there was nothing like the joy of seeing the Corps march by.
That's right.
It's just a totally different environment.
And I had to be over there at the football games because most of the people were there.
And the traffic, people fussed about it there.
And I was still going to midnight yell practice because I was still in
under the, had the, you know, leaders under my advisory capacity.
And those sort of things were a pretty full day.
But, and it just wasn't the same feeling.
I wouldn't have, I wouldn't have stayed much longer in the River Coast.
Now you did that for how many years?
until I was 83.
83, so six years.
Dr. Miller, as president, what were your relations with him?
Not much.
I had very little to learn.
And so you reported directly to Coldus?
Until about
a year or so before I left, and they turned it over to Charcala, which I didn't like.
I don't mean it.
I didn't like him.
I liked being around Dr. Coles.
I don't blame him.
I'd have shed a stir if I could have.
When he had a staff meeting, did you meet with the other people that reported to him?
Anytime Dr. Coles had a meeting, we all met.
Give this description a sample of the kinds of problems, big and small, that campus security had to deal with.
Well, the big problem, of course, again, was the traffic problem.
The police hated it.
And they were all commissioned policemen.
They didn't think it was their job.
And they were writing their tickets and listening to the hassle.
And really, it was a real hassle.
As far as security of the university was concerned, there weren't many problems.
We'd had a few break-ins and damages here and there.
very rare, once in a while there was a bomb threat, but not more than half a dozen times during my tenure.
We just, mostly it was the animosity towards us that made it a different job to have.
And it was really not fair, but I can understand it.
And like when I come to camp, I don't have any place to park.
I'd go pay for it.
The police at that time weren't paying for a parking permit.
I said, no way.
If everybody else on campus is paying, you're going to pay if you want to bring your car in here to work.
That caused a hassle.
They had one of the sergeants that was afraid
He wouldn't work at night because he was afraid of the dark, I guess, or something.
And we put him on shift.
If you don't like the shift, out you go.
And he said, well, you know, I can be on the day shift and the other one.
I said, well, shifts are going to be rotated every month.
And if somebody wants a swap shift, as long as the chief agrees, that's all right.
But, oh, and also Chief Luther, well, Luther,
wouldn't put women on duty at night.
And I said, why not?
They're police officers and they wanted to.
And so we put women on duty.
I mean, if they're going to be a policeman, they're going to be a policeman.
So, you know, there was, there were a lot of little things like that that were going on in there.
You know, you got to treat everybody what the job demands.
Now we, during your years, we didn't have any major problem like murders.
Well, we had, you know, one person was killed over in the chapel, one student, but they knew who it was.
No major fires other than the board room that I know of, or the board house.
But that was an accident.
Right.
We had a couple of
of reported rapes and that we were able to show that there was not a rape.
Once in a while, a fight would break out and I could go take care of it.
No weapons problems.
We had a lot of drug problems.
And what drugs primarily was it?
Oh, mostly marijuana, although once in a while you'd have a heroin.
And the marijuana, I didn't know what marijuana smelled like, you know.
But I, when I went through the police academy, that's one of the things you got to,
experience and I smoked a marijuana cigarette to experience what the smell was.
I didn't get any effect from it, I don't know, but anyway, that sort of stuff.
As far as y'all were aware, where was the marijuana coming from?
What was the source?
I don't know.
I don't know where it was, why it was.
Don't know who the... And any heroin, cocaine, any
I don't know of any ties with the drug, but Bob White probably, he might have known some of those things because he was in that business.
Well, and I'll bet it's a lot worse now than it was then.
Do you remember any goofy, funny, silly things that y'all coped with?
Not really.
I know it's not really funny because it's sad, but my youngest son got hooked on drugs, and he was a student and married.
They brought him in one night and called me at home about 2 o'clock in the morning.
I came over there, and he was still pretty high on whatever he was on.
And he starts cussing me, and I told him, you're not going to ever say that to me again.
And he did it again.
There was a policeman there with me, and I hauled off and knocked him on his butt.
And the policeman said, don't do that, you're a policeman, you're a policeman.
I said, get the hell out of here, I'm his father.
And anyway, he secured a scar with him the rest of his life up there, but he remembered that it was wrong.
But that wasn't funny, though.
It was just a sad thing.
And police business is not a fun thing.
I admire people.
Like Elmer Snyder, they got a jewel there.
Did anybody ever try to twist the arm of the campus police to get you to do something?
Well, I was working.
A lot of times I'd help them out at the front when we had these massive crowds.
And there was one of these, I don't even know what country he was from.
He was not U.S.
But he comes in once one of those,
parking lots where you have a number.
I said, you can't have one.
Well, what do they cost?
And I said, it doesn't matter what they cost, you can't have one.
And he pulled out his billfold and started putting $100, how much are they?
$100 bills down.
And I said, hold on a second.
I pulled out my badge and I said, now what was it you were saying?
Because I'd arrested him then, but I didn't want to do it at that time.
And he said, well, I'll just have to look somewhere else.
So he left.
But that actually happened.
Did any regent or former student or legislator ever tell you?
Oh, not the big guys.
The regents were nice people.
Of course, we always took care of them, too, in the boardroom when they had that number one plaque.
But people were always trying to get you to take care of their tickets or the car was towed or one thing or another.
The only thing I told him, I said, my son's gotten a couple of tickets, and he paid them.
I didn't ultimately pay them, but my wife got two or three, and she paid them.
And that's the only way you can operate.
You just can't do anything else.
Did you ever get any calls from somebody trying to get you to let their son go?
Well, I guess, let's see, Gus Majalis,
Gus's son was a student here, and it was a petty thing, but he picked up a passbook, I guess a student book with football tickets in it, and didn't turn it in.
And it was pretty easy to find out who it belonged to.
It was in the reserve section over there, and they found him, and we were taken down to JP like everybody else.
We didn't get to the JP.
It was taken care of before we got there.
But I didn't know that they had a direct line through Maddox.
Mm.
Maddox was the land where the athletic department.
Mm.
And, you know, we, I, every coach I went to, and I said, if Fort Lauderdale football coaches, players are the same as any other student, and we're going to treat them the same.
It didn't happen that way.
And before we tried to, before we got to J.P. with them, it was taken care of, and Maddox was telling them about it.
And, I mean, I hope it didn't happen to now.
I don't think it is.
When the old board house burned, how did you hear about that fire?
Well, they called me at home.
Do you remember who called?
Oh, the police.
I was the policeman.
They called me, and I jumped in the truck and headed out.
And it was, you know, of course, still burning when I got here.
And thank goodness no one was injured, were they?
No, no.
You know, the college station pilot was probably one of the best.
And, of course, that thing was fully engulfed, too.
By the time I got there, I don't know what all happened.
I know that, of course, I saw Dr. Miller's room, and they were very distraught, and, you know, just terrible life for them.
And Dr. Miller served until 1980.
Dr. Vandiver, yeah.
And then Dr. Vandiver...
What was it like reporting to him?
Well, I never had much direct conversation with him, but I disagreed with him.
You know, he wanted some guns, pistol.
And the police get a special price, and they wanted the police price, and I told them no.
I told the chief that, well, he got his guns, and he turned them in after all the trouble, and he came up and told them, well, here's your damn guns.
But the money that was paid for them came from former students.
He wanted somebody to, he wanted a police radio in his car, which I guess was all right.
The only thing is he used it for a lot more than that, to call my wife and tell her to do so and so, and that sort of stuff, which is kind of gauzy.
Little things like that were, I guess he somehow admired police people, and he used to,
McDonald used to take him out to the range and he'd shoot his pistol out there and that sort of stuff.
He was having some problems with her former husband, and I walked around his house several nights, two or three hours, looking for suspicious characters that were out there.
We'd get phone calls that somebody was running across that path.
That was a jogging path.
But nevertheless, we'd go out there, and I went out to a little theft place that's over there, and wandered around for three hours, never saw anything.
But, and we were getting those same phone calls, threatening calls.
And during all of your years, we never had a serious theft problem here on the campus, did we?
Not there.
As far as you knew,
How did A&M as a campus, in terms of law enforcement, how did it compare with, in crime rate, compared to other universities?
Well, the larger universities like UT and University of Houston and so forth, we knew pretty much about them because we all were having an association.
They didn't have traffic.
They were police.
And they were totally different problems.
These smaller universities were combined.
A&M was just too big for that type of operation.
So we couldn't compare with them.
And you can't compare with the quality.
You train them and somebody else will hire them because they don't like it.
And I mean, it costs a lot to train these guys and put them in the uniform.
And by the time you get them in the uniform, you've already spent several thousand dollars.
And then they're very employable because they're the high turnover of police people.
Brian College Station hired a bunch of our people.
And generally, where did our university police, what was their background?
Where did they come from?
Well, young guys out looking for a job.
Most of them were not college people.
And were they professionally trained police?
Well, no, we got very few that were already certified.
We had to send them to school.
And then quite often they got hired away by some of them.
Most of the time.
By the time you invest in uniforms for them and training and everything, because we didn't pay them as much when they were in school as we did when they were certified.
And as soon as they were certified, the same way that Brian in college, they'd yank them off for $1,000 more or something like that.
You can't blame the guys, but that's what happened.
So I gather in comparison of the two tasks you had here, being commandant was more satisfying.
Oh, it was a fun job.
And more enjoyable.
And so you left the second task in 1980.
And you left at a time when you decided.
Yes, I volunteered.
Although, frankly, I could see the handwriting on the wall because I think they were ready for a change over there and a couple of should have been made.
I made a mistake, like I said before.
I should not have put Russell McDonald in the job, and I should have moved him out of there, and I didn't.
All right.
As yesterday, if you were offering advice to people today about what the commandant should do, what advice would you give them?
Well, it looks to me like he's got the best of both worlds now.
He's got financial aid, and that was a big problem.
And he's got a staff that makes me very envious.
They're all good people.
They're all falling over 98% Aggie, maybe 100.
And they all are military oriented.
And the ROTC business, they've got it great, too.
All they've got to worry about is their class.
So I think his biggest problem is recruiting and retention.
And with the scholarship program and the shortage of space and everything, I think recruiting must not be too difficult.
And would you always have the Commandant be a former Aggie student?
I would like for him to be, if I had any choice.
What about branch of service?
Doesn't matter.
Doesn't matter?
The Commandant's supposed to be not prejudiced.
You can help with a little service bias, but I don't think it matters.
General Darling, I thought he did a great job.
And General Hopgood, he's been very good to me.
About how long would you have the commandant serve?
I think five or six years is enough.
Just like presidents of universities, there's a time when you get pretty stale in the job.
It's really the same thing over and over and over.
More so in the corps probably than in the academia.
What about advising about police and that task?
What advice would you give there to the decision makers?
Oh, I wouldn't be, I'm not near as professional in the policemen as Bob Wildman.
Elmer Snyder is my closest friend here now, and I spent a lot of time with him, and Elmer, he really works hard at that job, and Bob, I like Bob a lot, but I wish he'd retire.
It's time for him to retire, because Elmer's doing the job, and it wouldn't matter, he'll still do the job either way, but
But they've got a fantastic organization, and those guys have got to have at least two years of college.
And they're not friendly.
When you see them on the campus, they don't speak or anything like that, which I think is kind of wrong, because you don't need to walk around like I'm a policeman.
Don't mess with me.
And I see that.
And I noticed it myself just this morning.
I spoke to a couple of them and got ignored.
But I speak to a lot of the people I didn't get ignored to.
And like you were telling me, I've been noticing the girls, they smile and speak to you.
And that makes me feel good.
Looking over those years and both tasks, what were your happiest, proudest moments?
Well, one of them was this thing right here.
which I see you're wearing, too.
And I know that... As a note to the machine, he pointed to the watch for the Distinguished Service Award, and in his case was for University Service.
It's really Student Relations.
Student Relations Award, yes.
There's one a year.
And I know that there were people that objected to a military force from getting it.
And I didn't even know who some of them were, which is fine.
I was surprised and everything else.
But I was very proud of the guys in the student body that I know who were behind my getting this thing.
And they're pretty influential people in Washington right now, as you know who one of them is.
But it really was an unexpected thing.
And also, it will never happen again to an active duty military officer because you've got to have five years of the university.
And I don't think that's going to ever happen again.
So I had the longest tenure of any military active duty person.
Other proud moments, happy moments?
Well, the Carroll time, of course, was a very proud moment for me.
I was very proud when, I guess, when Judy graduated.
She had never been to college, never hoped to go.
She was scared to death.
I told her when I went to work for the University Police, I said, okay, I haven't had time to do anything else and I want you to go to college.
And I carried her around to some of the profs
And they said, you can do it.
Don't worry.
Well, I don't remember much and whatever, but anyway, she just needed it.
Now, this is your daughter?
No, I'm the only person you know who's been married three times and never divorced.
Oh, oh, oh.
My second wife.
Oh, oh, that's right.
That's right.
I'm sorry.
Yes, yes.
And Judy, she graduated cum laude in industrial ed.
And I was very proud of that.
At the same time, we still had three boys at home, too, and I don't know how she did it.
Of course, I was proud when my son graduated, and when I married again, I was very proud.
Carlos, he'll be there tonight, and he's an Aggie all the way through.
I'm very proud of what he's going to do now and be a nurse.
I think that's a good application.
And of course this thing here was a...
The petition, yes.
That was a very moving thing for me.
Of all the presidents that you observed, to which ones would you give the highest
Well, of course, Dr. Williams is the one that I knew the most and really knew him well, as well as you can know him in that relationship, not in a personal relationship.
But I didn't have much personal dealings with Dr. Miller or Dr. Vander, but Dr. Williams almost on a daily basis.
And are there some
If you were writing a list of people to whom you feel deepest gratitude connected with A&M, who would that be?
Well, of course, Buck, not around anymore, Buck Wirus.
Buck Wirus, oh.
And because he was very supportive of me and the Corps.
And again, Dr. Williams and John DeColtis were supportive.
And, you know, all over the campus, most of the faculty were very, very supportive.
I'm sure there were some that didn't like it.
I know they hated like hell having us on the faculty council or whatever it is.
Heck, we didn't want to be there anyway.
But we felt like we better be there because voting on things, I didn't know what they were talking about.
There's just so many good things that happened in the world.
It's hard to say.
All right, now I've run out of questions.
What else have we not covered from?
Yes, I don't know.
I think we've covered about everything I can think of.
Well, let's end then with what do you think about A&M's future?
Well, it looks awfully bright to me, I think, educationally.
And what I'm glad of is that the students haven't changed.
They're the same good people.
And the campus is so different from any other place I've ever been.
I haven't spent much time on university campuses, but I did spend two years at Boston College.
And there's no difference from those people back then, even.
But I think we're just going to be
We're going to stay on the top.
We may not be a Harvard or a Yale, but I'd rather be from here than Harvard or Yale.
I don't think our education is any less than what they get.
They just get a better name, maybe.
But I do want it to not grow much bigger, though.
That's a good thing.
